### Description

*TOTAL SITE FAILURE*

We came across a major compatibility issue on several customer sites running Angular. Our code is utilizing `queueMicrotask` as part of initialization. When opening an `XMLHttpRequest` within a subsequent microtask the browser CPU spikes due to recursively calling `queueMicrotask`. This only happens on Zone-enabled sites.

To reproduce, paste the following code into the console on one of the following sites: LandsEnd.com, Avery.com, PapaGinos.com:

```
(function() {
  "use strict";
  let _isDispatching = false;
  function run() {
    function dispatch(event) {
      console.log("in dispatch for loggerString", event);
      if (_isDispatching) {
        console.log("already dispatching, queuing string", event);
        queueMicrotask(() => dispatch(event));
        console.log("queued string", event);
        return;
      }
      _isDispatching = true;
      if (event === "init") {
        dispatch("extra event");
        const xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
        xhr.open("GET", "google.com", true);
      }
      _isDispatching = false;
    }
    dispatch("init");
  }
  run();
})();
```

In attempting to create as small a reproduction as possible, I used a stock CLI app and was able to recreate the issue with a larger piece of code. However, once narrowing down to this smaller example code, we weren't able to replicate in a toy app. Happy to attempt to help find out more about the incompatibility, but right now this is as far as we were able to get in terms of narrowing down the use case.

